{{notability|Org|date=June 2011}}

'''The Association for Legalizing American Lotteries''' was an illegal [[Lotteries in the United States|lottery]] disguised as an organization in 1936.

==History==
[[Thomas George Lanphier, Sr.]] was president.<ref name=third/> They organized the Grand National Treasure Hunt and sold tickets for $1 disguised as "applications for membership" to circumvent the prohibition on lotteries.<ref name=stakes>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title= Stakes & Sweeps |url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,848481-1,00.html |quote= |publisher=[[Time (magazine)|Time]] |date=April 20, 1936 |accessdate=2007-08-21 }}</ref> The prize for their third lottery was $37,500 (approximately ${{formatnum:{{Inflation|US|37500|1936|r=-3}}}} today).<ref name=third>{{cite news |author= |agency= |title=Prize Of $37,500 Won By Housemaid |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1936/06/09/archives/prize-of-37500-won-by-housemaid-she-and-husband-a-chauffeur-plan.html |quote= |newspaper=[[New York Times]] |date=June 9, 1936 |accessdate=2016-09-10 }}</ref> The [[United States Post Office]] charged them with fraud in 1936, the case was appealed in ''Association for Legalizing American Lotteries v. Goldman, 85 F.2d 67 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] 1936)'' and was decided against the association on July 17, 1936.<ref name=stakes/>

